.TH FLAG 1 "2023-04-18" "1.0" "flag man page"

.SH NAME
flag - parse command line flags and convert them to variables

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B . flag
.br
.B flag "[-a][-b][-c][-A <value>][-B <value>][-C <value>] ..."

.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fBflag\fP utility parses command line flags and converts them to easy to use variables. It is intended to be used within other scripts, by sourcing the "flag" script with the dot command, followed by calling the "flag" function and passing a string of valid flag options.

The lower case letters are boolean flags and the upper case letters take an argument. There is no support for long options like "--foo" or "--bar". The variables set will be of the form "flag_[flag]", for example "flag_a" for flag "-a".

The \fBflag\fP utility is distributed under the MIT license, with credits attribution required. The author is "Amosnimos".

.SH EXAMPLES
To use the \fBflag\fP utility within another script, source the "flag" script with the dot command:
.br
.B . flag
.br
Then, call the "flag" function and pass a string of valid flag options:
.br
.B flag "[-a][-b][-c][-A <value>][-B <value>][-C <value>] ..."

.SH SEE ALSO
getopts(1)

.SH AUTHOR
The \fBflag\fP utility was written by Amosnimos.
